<div class="jumbotron jumbotron-news-landing">
  <div class="container container-padded container-fluid">
    <div class="pfda-cards pfda-cards-align-centered pfda-cards-stretch">
      <div class="pfda-card pfda-challenge-card pfda-card-default pfda-card-rounded pfda-card-bordered pfda-card-padded pfda-card-shadow">
        <div class="media">
          <h3 class="text-center">PrecisionFDA CFSAN Pathogen Detection Challenge</h3>
          <div class="pfda-challenge-diagram">
            <img src="/assets/challenges/pFDA-nci-cptac-Diagram.png" alt="PrecisionFDA Mislabelling Challenge">
          </div>
          <div class="media-body pfda-padded">
            <div class="pfda-card-body text-justify">
              <div>
                Prepare to join the Challenge that utilizes multiple types of omics data to detect and correct mislabeled data.
              </div>
              <br>
              <div>
                In biomedical research, sample mislabeling or incorrect annotation has been a long-standing problem that contributes to irreproducible results and invalid conclusions. These problems are particularly prevalent in large scale multi-omics studies, in which multiple different omics experiments are carried out at different time periods and/or in different labs. Human sample labeling or annotation errors could arise during sample transferring, sample tracking, large-scale data generation, and data sharing/management. There is a pressing need to have computation programs to automatically screen for and to correct such incorrect sample labels or annotations. The goal of this challenge is to develop computational algorithms that can accurately detect and correct mislabeled data in large-scale multi-omics studies.
              </div>
              <br>
              <div>
                The challenge starts on September 24st!
              </div>
              <br>
              <p><%= link_to 'Click here to sign up for more information' , 'https://form.jotform.com/81827419821967', class: 'btn btn-primary', target: :_blank %></p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>